/*
ğŸ¯ WHAT YOU'LL LEARN:
How to "grab" HTML elements so JavaScript can work with them.

ğŸ“– EXPLANATION:
Your HTML has elements like <input id="taskInput">, but JavaScript
can't use them until you SELECT them first.

Think of it like this:
- Your HTML is a house with many rooms
- querySelector is like giving directions: "Go to the room with ID 'taskInput'"
- Once you find the room, you can interact with it!

ğŸ”§ THE TOOL: document.querySelector()

SYNTAX:
document.querySelector('#idName')
                        â†‘
                The # means "search by ID"

EXAMPLE:
If your HTML has: <button id="myButton">Click me</button>
You select it with: const btn = document.querySelector('#myButton');
Now 'btn' represents that button in JavaScript!
*/

